{{infobox winter storm |name= |image location=Nor'easter_1960-03-04_weather_map.jpg |image name=A [[surface weather analysis]] of the nor'easter on March 4 |stormtype= |date formed= |date dissipated= |RSI=14.53 |pressure= |maximum amount= |total damages (USD)= |total fatalities= |areas affected= }}
The '''March 1960 nor'easter''' was a severe winter storm that impacted the [[Mid-Atlantic States|Mid-Atlantic]] and [[New England]] regions of the [[United States]]. The storm ranked as Category 4, or "crippling", on the [[Northeast Snowfall Impact Scale]].<ref name="NCDC">{{cite web|author=|title=The Northeast Snowfall Impact Scale (NESIS)|date=|publisher=National Climatic Data Center|accessdate=March 1, 2010|url=http://www1.ncdc.noaa.gov/pub/data/cmb/images/snow/nesis/19600302-19600305-8.77.jpg}}</ref> Northeasterly flow, combined with the storm's slower forward motion, enhanced snowfall across the region.<ref name="Kocin 383">Kocin and Uccellini, p. 383</ref> The cyclone began moving away from the United States on March 5.<ref>{{cite web|author=|title=Saturday, March 5, 1960 daily weather map|date=March 5, 1960|publisher=NOAA Central Library Data Imaging Project|accessdate=March 1, 2010|url=http://docs.lib.noaa.gov/rescue/dwm/1960/19600305.djvu}}</ref> It took place during a stormy period in the affected region,<ref name="Kocin 384">Kocin and Uccellini, p. 384</ref> contributing to record snowfall.<ref name="snow">{{cite web|author=L. Baker Perry and Charles E. Konrad|title=Synoptic Patterns Associated with the Record Snowfall of 1960 in the Southern Appalachians|date=|publisher=Eastern Snow|accessdate=March 1, 2010|url=http://www.easternsnow.org/proceedings/2006/perry_and_konrad.pdf}}</ref>
==Impact== The storm's impacts were wide-reaching; snow accumulated from the southeastern United States through northern New England.<ref name="NCDC"/> Totals exceeding {{convert|10|in|cm|abbr=on}} were reported from [[West Virginia]] to [[Maine]], while snowfall of over {{convert|20|in|cm|abbr=on}} fell in parts of eastern [[Massachusetts]], [[Rhode Island]], northern [[Connecticut]], southern [[New Hampshire]], northern [[New Jersey]] and southeastern [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref name="Kocin 383"/><ref name="Kocin 384"/> [[Nantucket, Massachusetts]] reported {{convert|31.3|in|cm|abbr=on}} of snow, the most on record.<ref>http://capeandislands.org/post/eight-historic-new-england-march-snowstorms</ref> Blizzard conditions organized in eastern Massachusetts, accompanied by intense winds.<ref name="Kocin 383"/> The storm caused at least 80 fatalities and stranded thousands of residents. Schools were forced to close, and transportation was severely disrupted. Stalled vehicles on roadways hampered snow removal efforts. [[New York City]] received the most severe winter storm since 1948.<ref name="severe blizzard">{{cite web|author=Staff Writer|title=Savage Snowstorm Buries Northeast|date=March 4, 1960|publisher=''The Sarasota Journal''|accessdate=March 1, 2010|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=1gIdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=8YoEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5575,474865&dq=march+snowstorm+1960&hl=en}}</ref> Many commuters in [[Manhattan]] became marooned.<ref>{{cite web|author=Staff Writer|title=Coast States Severely Hit|date=March 4, 1960|publisher=''The Southeast Missourian''|accessdate=March 1, 2010|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=1rEfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PdcEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1680,5002132&dq=march+snowstorm+1960&hl=en}}</ref> Major airports closed during the storm, resulting in the cancellation of hundreds of flights.<ref>{{cite web|author=Staff Writer|title=Northeast Digs Out of Big Snow|date=March 6, 1960|publisher=''The Nevada Daily Mail''|accessdate=March 1, 2010|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=jWIfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=p9QEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1042,2592188&dq=march+snowstorm+1960&hl=en}}</ref>
