{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}} {{Infobox Government agency |agency_name = Ministry of Energy, Industry and Mineral Resources |type = Ministrial Department |logo = Ministry_of_Petroleum_and_Mineral_Resources_Logo_-_Saudi_Arabia.png |logo_width = |logo_caption = Logo of the Ministry |seal = |seal_width = |seal_caption = |formed = {{start date and age|1960|12|1|df=yes}} |preceding1 = Directorate General of Petroleum and Mineral Affairs |preceding2 = Ministry of Petroleum and Mineral Resources |dissolved = |superseding = |jurisdiction =[[Saudi Arabia]] |headquarters = [[Riyadh]] |employees = |budget = |minister1_name =[[Khalid A. Al-Falih]] |minister1_pfo = Minister |child1_agency = |child2_agency = |child3_agency = |website = [http://www.meim.gov.sa/arabic/Pages/default.aspx Official website] |footnotes = }}
The '''Ministry of Energy, Industry and Mineral Resources''' is one of the governmental bodies of [[Saudi Arabia]] and part of [[Cabinet of Saudi Arabia|the cabinet]]. The ministry has the function of developing and implementing policies concerning [[petroleum]] and [[petroleum products|related products]].
==History== The ministry was established in December 1960.<ref name=Oron>{{cite book|author=Yitzhak Oron, Ed.|title=Middle East Record Volume 2, 1961|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vzZ71Eh5QvMC&pg=PA419|accessdate=16 September 2013|publisher=The Moshe Dayan Center|pages=419|id=GGKEY:4Q1FXYK79X8}}</ref><ref name=rad>{{cite web|title=Ministry of Petroleum and Mineral Resources|url=http://www.saudinf.com/main/c6u.htm|work=SAMIRAD|accessdate=16 September 2013}}</ref> Prior to the formation of the ministry policies regarding oil production and planning were overseen by the directorate general of petroleum and mineral affairs which was attached to the ministry of finance.<ref name=sher/> Then the directorate was converted into the ministry.<ref name=sher/> The ministry was named the Ministry of Petroleum and Mineral Resources until May 2016 when it was renamed as the Ministry of Energy, Industry and Mineral Resources.<ref name="reut"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.industryarabic.com/arab-ministries-the-complete-list/|title=Arab Ministries: The Complete English-Arabic List - Industry Arabic|date=2018-04-13|work=Industry Arabic|access-date=2018-05-07|language=en-US}}</ref>
The ministry is based in [[Riyadh]].<ref> [http://www.s-ge.com/de/filefield-private/files/2816/field_blog_public_files/4865 Basic addresses] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140224033210/http://www.s-ge.com/de/filefield-private/files/2816/field_blog_public_files/4865 |date=24 February 2014 }} OSCE. September 2011. Retrieved 5 February 2014.</ref>
===List of ministers=== Since 1960 the ministry was headed by the following five ministers: # [[Abdullah Tariki]] (December 1960 - 9 March 1962)<ref name=Oron/> # [[Ahmed Zaki Yamani]] (9 March 1962 – 5 October 1986)<ref name=sher>{{cite journal|last=Hertog|first=Steffen|title=Petromin: the slow death of statist oil development in Saudi Arabia|url=http://eprints.lse.ac.uk/29865/1/Petromin_the_Slow_Death_of_Statist_Oil_Development_in_Saudi_Arabia_(LSERO).pdf|journal=Business history|year=2008|volume=50|issue=5|pages=645–667|doi=10.1080/00076790802246087|accessdate=16 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Defining moments: Sheikh Yamani|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/3055760.stm|accessdate=16 September 2013|newspaper=BBC|date=9 July 2003}}</ref> # [[Hisham Nazer]] (24 December 1986 – 2 August 1995)<ref>{{cite news|title=Key ministers fired as king cleans house|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=5UZWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=GOsDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3224,365636&dq=hisham+nazer&hl=en|accessdate=16 September 2013|newspaper=Eugene Register Guard|date=3 August 1995|agency=AP|location=Riyadh}}</ref> # [[Ali Al-Naimi|Ali Naimi]] (2 August 1995 – 7 May 2016)<ref name="reut">{{cite news|title=Saudi Arabia names Khalid al-Falih energy minister to replace Naimi|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-oil-minister-idUSKCN0XY0E1|accessdate=8 May 2016|work=Reuters|date=7 May 2016}}</ref> # [[Khalid A. Al-Falih]] (7 May 2016 - present)<ref name="reut"/>
==Organization and activities== The ministry is primarily responsible for the policies concerning oil, gas and natural minerals in the country which is the world's largest holder of crude oil reserves.<ref name=eia>{{cite web|title=Saudi Arabia|url=http://www.eia.gov/countries/analysisbriefs/Saudi_Arabia/saudi_arabia.pdf|work=US Energy Information Administration|accessdate=16 September 2013|date=26 February 2013}}</ref> It closely monitors the activities of [[Saudi Aramco|the Saudi Aramco]] together with the Supreme Council for Petroleum and Minerals.<ref name=eia/> However, the ministry has much more responsibility in this regard than the council.<ref name=rwi>{{cite web|title=Saudi Arabia|url=http://www.revenuewatch.org/countries/middle-east-and-north-africa/saudi-arabia/overview|work=Revenue Watch Institution|accessdate=16 September 2013}}</ref>
The other agency with which the ministry works is [[Petromin Corporation|Petromin]], the general petroleum and mineral organization.<ref name=rad/> Through [[SABIC|Saudi Arabian Basic Industries Company]] (SABIC), established in 1976, the ministry oversaw the operation of [[petrochemicals]] and other [[heavy industry]] projects.<ref name=sher/>
