{{about|power per volume|power per unit mass|power-to-weight ratio|power per area|surface power density}}
{{Infobox physical quantity | name = Power density | unit = [[watt|W]]/[[meter|m]]<sup>3</sup> | basequantities = kg·m<sup>−1</sup>s<sup>−3</sup> | symbols = | derivations = [[power (physics)|P]]/[[volume|V]] }}
'''Power density''' (or ''volume power density'' or ''volume specific power'') is the amount of [[Power (physics)|power]] (time rate of [[energy transfer]]) per unit [[volume]].
In [[energy transformation|energy transformers]] including [[battery (electricity)|batteries]], [[fuel cell]]s, motors, etc., and also [[power supply]] units or similar, power density refers to a volume. It is then also called '''volume power density''', which is expressed as W/m<sup>3</sup>.
Volume power density is sometimes an important consideration where space is constrained.
In [[reciprocating engine|reciprocating]] [[internal combustion engine]]s, power density—power per [[swept volume]] or [[brake horsepower per cubic centimeter]] —is an important metric. This is based on the ''internal'' capacity of the engine, not its external size.
